# Module tRPC File Style Guide

Conventions for tRPC router files in app modules. Routers are thin wiring:
they attach the module DTO schemas and delegate to the service. The router is
also the type source for the client — the webapp infers all row/list types
from `AppRouter`, so accurate `.input()`/`.output()` here is what makes
end-to-end types work.

## File Location

```
apps/<app>/server/src/modules/<module>/<module>.trpc.ts
```

## Conventions

- Export a factory function named `create<Module>TRPC`.
- Import the module DTO object (`postSchemas`) from `./<module>.dto` — not
  shared schemas, not hand-written types.
- Use `handleTRPCResult` from `@m5kdev/backend/utils/trpc` to unwrap `Result`s.
- Keep resolvers one-liners that delegate to the service; no business logic or
  DB access here.
- Always pass `ctx` to service methods as the second argument. The first
  argument (`input`) can be `undefined` for optional-input queries.

## Factory Pattern

```typescript
import { handleTRPCResult, type TRPCMethods } from "@m5kdev/backend/utils/trpc";
import { postSchemas } from "./posts.dto";
import type { PostsService } from "./posts.service";

export function createPostsTRPC(
  { router, privateProcedure: procedure }: TRPCMethods,
  postsService: PostsService
) {
  return router({
    list: procedure
      .input(postSchemas.input.list)
      .output(postSchemas.output.list)
      .query(async ({ ctx, input }) => handleTRPCResult(await postsService.list(input ?? {}, ctx))),

    create: procedure
      .input(postSchemas.input.create)
      .output(postSchemas.output.single)
      .mutation(async ({ ctx, input }) => handleTRPCResult(await postsService.create(input, ctx))),

    softDelete: procedure
      .input(postSchemas.input.delete)
      .output(postSchemas.output.uuid)
      .mutation(async ({ ctx, input }) =>
        handleTRPCResult(await postsService.softDelete(input, ctx))
      ),
  });
}
```

## Procedure Selection

- `privateProcedure` — authenticated user (most module routes).
- `organizationProcedure` — requires an active organization.
- `adminProcedure` — admin role.
- `publicProcedure` — unauthenticated; use sparingly.

The service's own `.requireAuth()`/`.access()` still run — the tRPC procedure
choice is transport-level gating, not a replacement for service checks.
